INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('60adc73b4b850e95', 'Someone great, once said "I love human beings, it is the people that I hate".?', 'No es una cita exacta de un solo autor. Sin embargo, el sentimiento se atribuye com├║nmente a **Fi├│dor Dostoievski**, a menudo a trav├⌐s de su personaje **Iv├ín Karamazov** en *Los hermanos Karamazov*.', 'The original of the quote is "I love humanity, but I hate people". This great someone is Edna St. Vincent Millay, an American poet.\n\nWhat she probably meant was: humanity as an abstract ideal relates and appeals to all of us, and the collective efforts of humanity and the ideal of human being is therefore subject to love and care. \n\nHowever "people", the name given to group of indivudals who contribute to humanity spoils all things idealistic that relates to humanity, defying its own existence. It''''s possible to observe, measure and judge people, but humanity as a whole is blameless from the acts of people.\n\nSo the quote is basically a play on idealism and realism, how people don''''t deserve umbrella terms like humanity, how they suck, how they don''''t understand us, yada yada. \n\nThe problem with this attitude is that it excludes the term humanity from the undesired acts of the people, while involving the desired ones. Yet, Humanity itself is responsible of "bad things" as well. Although Humanity has a "good" connotation, it does not, and should not encompass "good", or only good. It is and should remain a neutral term. \n\nSo if you hate people, you also hate humanity for it is people who amount to it. If you love humanity, it''''s very hard to hate people, for it''''s people who contribute to humanity.\n\nMaybe the joke is on that misunderstanding. But I am only human, I can make mistakes. Don''''t hate me for being wrong, but love my human side.', 0.5697048902511597, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 08:08:28.130347', '2025-09-16 08:08:28.130347');
