INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('48fb9dd8b6301a2e', 'HOW CAN WE IGNORE SMOKEING... CAN WE.............?', 'No, es innegable.', 'Can we?  Of course.  Humans have an amazing ability to rationalize almost any behavior, and there are limits on how much control we allow society to exercise on individual freedoms.\n\nTake alcohol for example.  Alcohol is a primary and secondary cause of death for thousands?  millions?  Well, a whole bunch of people die from alcoholism, drunk driving, and "I can too jump off this roof!" every year, but we allow it.  And, as with smoking, the deaths and injuries suffered are not always suffered by the imbiber.\n\nWe have taken an entirely different tack with the "war on drugs."  Even though there is little real difference between smoking, drinking, and illegal drug use on principle, (though the effects of some drugs are far worse of course) we have decided to ban those substances.\n\nThe plain truth is that as long as humans are recognizably like us, they will seek altered states of consciousness through chemical and other means, whether it''''s a heroin high, alcoholic buzz, the calm of nicotine, tweaking on caffeine, or getting a euphoric rush from "the choking game."  \n\nI am no fan of smoking, but consider well the drug war and prohibition in the last century before attempting to legislate away tobacco.  A whole criminal industry grows up around banned substances that may well cause worse damage as a whole than the habit.', 0.546718180179596, 2, 1000, '2025-09-16 14:46:11.399248', '2025-09-16 14:46:11.399248');
INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('668973896250da25', 'how do computer networks work?', 'Las redes de computadoras conectan dispositivos (computadoras, impresoras, etc.) mediante cables o Wi-Fi. Utilizan un conjunto de reglas (protocolos como TCP/IP) para dividir la informaci├│n en peque├▒os paquetes. Estos paquetes contienen la direcci├│n de origen y destino, viajan por la red (guiados por routers y switches) hasta su destino, donde se reensamblan, permitiendo la comunicaci├│n y el intercambio de recursos.', 'That''''s really a complex question.  You might try to ask a few questions with a little more direct ideas.\n\n"Network" in general is just a connection of many single devices or computers.  There are basically two types of networks.  LANs (Local Area Network) with a set of computers connected in a private network.  Or WAN (Wide Area Network) of which the most popular WAN is the Internet, though this can be used to describe large networks over many locations.\n\nI''''ll stick to "LAN" for this explaination.  A LAN is a connection of a few or many computers in a private setting.  Like in a home you can connect two computers together with Windows XP by simply plugging both machines into a Switch or Router.  I recommend using a router as it provides a little more control over the network and allows a single broadband internet connection to work with both computers at the same time.  With Windows XP the setup of a network is fairly easy with little or no special actions required.  Just connect and it should work.\n\nOnce connected both computers can share information and pereferials like drives and printers.  To share a device, simply right click on the icon for that device and choose "sharing" in the menu that appears.\n\nI hope that this basic explaination helps.  Again, please ask more detailed questions for better indepth answers.', 0.6154999732971191, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 10:01:32.359683', '2025-09-16 10:01:32.359683');
