INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('0456292a2982e0f6', 'what is the defense mechanism of our respiratory system?', 'El principal es el **sistema mucociliar** (moco y cilios) que atrapa y expulsa part├¡culas y pat├│genos. Tambi├⌐n act├║an los **reflejos de tos y estornudo** para eliminar irritantes.', 'Many mechanisms play at the same time,\n1) Goblet cells secrete mucus that prevent invasion of pathogens.\n2) Cell junctions and the epithelial cells lining the mucosa form a continuous non-penetratable barrier to the pathogens.\n3) Epithelial cells produce IgA (immunoglobulin A) antibody against tens of thousands of antigens, IgA acts by neutralizing, precipitating or killing the invading pathogens (e.g. polio virus)\n4) Mucosal Blood Supply also forms important defense mechanism as it delivers antibodies, immunity cells and nutrients to the involved site.\n5) Macrophages and lymphocytes exists in the mucosa to provide defense against invading pathogens thru cell mediated and humoral immunity.\n6) Movement of cilia towards the pharynx causes the mucus layer to be removed and renewed every few hours. The mucus layer traps not only invading pathogens but also minute forign particle like dust which gain entry into the air passages.\n7) Reflex closure of laryngeal inlet by epiglottis, true and false vocal cords occurs in the absence of coughing plays very important role to prevent entry of foreign objects in the respiratory tract.\n8) Cough reflex, tends to expell out the foreign body if it enters into the respiratory tract (thus it behaves as secondary denfese mechanism)\n9) Nasal cilia (hairs) as mentioned above.', 0.6350184679031372, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 10:42:50.336936', '2025-09-16 10:42:50.336936');
