INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('30c1ab6d352d8792', 'When did India devolpe the caste system?', 'Surgi├│ durante el **per├¡odo V├⌐dico** (aproximadamente 1500-500 a.C.), consolid├índose y rigidiz├índose a lo largo de los siglos posteriores.', 'The caste system in India can be described as an elaborately stratified social hierarchy distinguishing IndiaΓÇÖs social structure from any other nation. Its history is multifaceted and complex.  \nCaste is a term, which is used to specify a group of people having a specific social rank and dates back to 1200 BCE. The Indian term for caste is jati, and generally designates a group that can vary in size from a handful to many thousands. There are thousands of jatis each with its own rules and customs. The various jatis are traditionally arranged in hierarchical order and fit into one of the four basic varnas the (Sanskrit word for ΓÇ£colorsΓÇ¥).   \n--The varna of Brahmans, commonly identified with priests and the learned class \n--The varna of Kshatriyas, associated with rulers and warriors including    property owners. \n--The varna of Vaishyas, associated with commercial livelihoods (i.e. traders) \n--The varna of Shudras, the servile laborers  \nThe Untouchables occupy a place that is not clearly defined by boundaries and is outside of the varna scheme. Their jobs (such as toilet cleaning and garbage removal) cause them to be considered impure and thus ΓÇ£untouchable.ΓÇ¥  Historically the untouchables were not allowed in temples and many other public places. In 1950 legislation was passed to prevent any form of discrimination towards the untouchables. Although legislation has affected the status of the people, they are yet very much a visible part of Indian society. \n\nhttp://www.mtholyoke.edu/~epandit/page2.html\n\nOrigins of the Caste System:\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caste_system#Origins_of_the_Caste_System', 0.5443977117538452, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 10:56:16.049755', '2025-09-16 10:56:16.049755');
INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('044098bd583d5756', 'What are they referring to in marketing when they talk about the "long tail."?', 'En marketing, la "cola larga" se refiere a la estrategia de vender **muchos productos de nicho o de baja demanda individual**. La suma de las ventas de estos numerosos ├¡tems puede superar la de los pocos **best-sellers** (la "cabeza").', 'Chris Anderson, from Wired magazine used the phrase, ''''the long tail'''', to describe "an example of an entirely new economic model" based on the abundance of consumer choices and product availability.\n\nThe idea boils down to the fact that consumers will support many more products than previously known, albeit at smaller numbers. BUT, this continual stream of purchases can create a very significant number of sales.', 0.677675187587738, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 10:56:16.388921', '2025-09-16 10:56:16.388921');
