INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('602417dc90e3366b', 'Who named the Earth?', 'Nadie en particular. El nombre "Tierra" deriva de palabras germ├ínicas antiguas que significan "suelo" o "terreno", y evolucion├│ con el tiempo.', 'According to Wikipedia:\n\n"The word Earth has cognates in many modern as well as defunct - including ancient - languages. Examples in modern tongues include aarde in Dutch and Erde in German. The root also has cognates in extinct languages such as ertha in Old Saxon and ert (meaning ''''ground'''') in Middle Irish. It is derived from Old English eor├░e. Taking into account metathesis, we can find cognates of the word Earth in the Latin terra and in the modern Romance Languages (i.e. tierra in Spanish).\n\nAlthough a link to such Indo-European languages has not been proved, several Semitic languages have similar-sounding words for Earth: aard in Arabic, irtsitu in Assyrian, araa in Aramaic, erets in Phoenician (which appears in the Mesha Stele), and ╫É╫¿╫Ñ (arets, or erets when followed by a noun modifier) in Hebrew."\n\nThe fact that Earth and not Water was used seems intuitive. The origins of the word Earth are very old, from a period when the known world was thought to be much less than it actually is, and [thought to be] primarily composed of land.', 0.616268515586853, 2, 1000, '2025-09-16 18:00:37.220157', '2025-09-16 18:00:37.220157');
