INSERT INTO public.responses (question_id, question_text, llm_response, original_answer, bert_score, processing_attempts, total_processing_time_ms, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('65c525fbecb36156', 'Are viruses also created by antivirus vendors to sell their product?', 'No. Los virus son creados por actores maliciosos (cibercriminales, grupos patrocinados por estados, etc.). Las empresas de antivirus se dedican a detectarlos y proteger a los usuarios de ellos. Crear sus propios virus destruir├¡a su credibilidad y su negocio.', 'Without going into the ethical aspects, there are two issues that come to mind:\n- Yes, creating viruses artificially would indeed boost the need for antiviruses. If nothing else, it would let them claim they block "more viruses than the competition". \n- But the most important asset that antivirus firms have is not their product. It''''s the trust their customers put into them. If that trust disappears, the firm might as well close its doors.\n\nConsidering the huge risk an AV company would take if it started creating and spreading viruses for the sake of drumming up some business, it seems unlikely any healthy company would chance it.\n\nHowever, by following a similar line of thought, Enron should never have happened. \nYet it did.\n\nPS: Many AV-matched patterns are patterns that match "lab viruses", aka theorical exercises that have never actually spread in the wild. It is plausible (likely) some of those were created by AV employees in the process of investigating and keeping sharp on virus technology. Considering they never endangered anyone, I don''''t think of it as a problem. However, they helped sharpen their employee skills, and possibly resulted in a better AV product, so, indirectly, they may have helped sell their product.', 0.6439974904060364, 1, 500, '2025-09-16 19:01:17.181816', '2025-09-16 19:01:17.181816');
